{  
  "response_text": "The count of households with social learning begins at 20, corresponding to the initialized E-RO-SL1 agents. This baseline group experiences significant spread in early steps (steps 5–20), with the most rapid increases observed in reduction in consumption. The count stabilizes near 35 by step 50, suggesting limited further adoption beyond the initial E-RO-SL1 cohort due to disabled social susceptibility. Despite stochastic rainfall variability (global-rain?=True), no sustained deviation above this plateau occurs, indicating climate shocks do not catalyze additional learning behavior under current behavioral constraints. Variance across simulation runs remains minimal throughout, reflecting the deterministic nature of agent interactions within fixed parameter bounds. The absence of global strategy switching (SL2-strategy-switch?=False) likely constrained behavioral hybridization, while risk-averse configurations (risk-att-init=0.5) discouraged exploratory adoption. This stabilization contrasts with the system’s ecological subsystems, where biomass dynamics would exhibit greater fluctuation under identical climatic stress."  
}

